The complete list of CUDA dlls isn't actually known to ORT. Some additional ones may be internally loaded by the CUDA dlls as they execute, and those don't show up as explicit dependencies. For example with the model I tested, during execution the CUDA code needed to load cudnn_cnn_infer64_8.dll (and that also has a dependency on zlibwapi.dll). 

As such it's easier to make sure the complete CUDA install directory is in the path and those dlls aren't copied to the build output directory. Alternatively you would need to figure out the complete list of CUDA dlls by copying the explicit dependencies and then working through any errors during execution for other missing ones.

You can check node assignments by setting logging to VERBOSE in the session options. When the model is loaded there will be a message saying which nodes are assigned to the CUDA EP. 

```c#
            so.LogSeverityLevel = OrtLoggingLevel.ORT_LOGGING_LEVEL_VERBOSE;
```

Based on this output all nodes were assigned to GPU.

ORT CUDA EP requires both CUDA and cuDNN. It could be said more explicitly on https://onnxruntime.ai/docs/execution-providers/CUDA-ExecutionProvider.html#requirements instead of you having to infer it from the two columns in the version info table.

There are a long list of rules for how/where a library can be loaded. Using PATH works for me with all the CUDA and cuDNN dlls in one directory (as per the cuDNN install instructions which says to copy files to the CUDA install paths).

Regarding speed, how are you creating the input values? The 'ToTensor' helpers are horribly inefficient. Fixed in the lastest code but that isn't in the 1.10 release. 

When we execute the input data needs to be copied from CPU to CUDA and the results from CUDA to CPU. That device copy time can be significant if the model is fast. If you can batch up some images that should reduce the per-image overhead. 

When measuring performance to compare CPU vs CUDA make sure it's just for the InferenceSession.Run. CPU won't have the device copy overhead in that call so it's possible CPU can be faster for smaller models (although for yolov5l I wouldn't expect that to be the case).
